07886nam a22011895i 9783110331707DE-B159720221201113901.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221201t20152015gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)911214885  a97831103317077 a10.1515/97831103317072doi  a(DE-B1597)212925  a(OCoLC)909907809  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aDS324.K47bG74 2015 7aHIS0260202bisacsh04a955/.900aGreater Khorasan :bHistory, Geography, Archaeology and Material Culture /ced. by Rocco Rante. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (310 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in the History and Culture of the Middle East ,x2198-0853 ;v2900tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tTable of Contents -- tPre-Mongol Khurasan. A Historical Introduction -- t“Khorasan Proper” and “Greater Khorasan” within a politico-cultural framework -- tLa crise d’aridité climatique de la fin du 3ème millénaire av. J.-C., à la lumière des contextes géomorphologique de 3 sites d’Iran Oriental (Bam, Tepe Damghani, Jiroft) -- tFrom Parthian to Islamic Nisa -- tMerv on Khorasanian trade routes from the 10th–13th centuries -- tAncient Herat Revisited. New Data from Recent Archaeological Fieldwork -- tTrois mosquées du début de l’ère islamique au Grand Khorassan : Bastam, Noh-Gonbadan/Haji-Piyadah de Balkh et Zuzan d’après des investigations archéologiques -- tLe paysage urbain de Nishapur -- tNouvelles recherches sur la céramique de Nishapur : la prospection du shahrestan -- tArchaeological Material in the Museum Setting: The Metropolitan Museum of Art’s Excavations at Nishapur -- tNishapur Ceramics in the Metropolitan Museum of Art: 70 years of Restoration Techniques -- tLe Grand Khorasan : Datation par des méthodes physico-chimiques (carbone 14 et luminescence) -- tIndex -- tMaps0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe modern sense of “Greater Khorasan” today corresponds to a territory which not only comprises the region in the east of Iran but also, beyond Iranian frontiers, a part of Afghanistan and Turkmenistan. In the past this entity was simply defined as Khorasan. In the Sassanid era Khorasan defined the “Eastern lands”. In the Islamic era this term was again taken up in the same sense it previously enjoyed. The Arab sources of the first centuries all mention the eastern regions under the same toponym, Khorasan. Khorasan was the gateway used by Alexander the Great to go into Bactria and India and, inversely, that through which the Seljuks and Mongols entered Iran. In a diachronic context Khorasan was a transit zone, a passage, a crossroads, which, above all in the medieval period, saw the creation of different commercial routes leading to the north, towards India, to the west and into China. In this framework, archaeological researches will be the guiding principle which will help us to take stock of a material culture which, as its history, is very diversified. They also offer valuable elements on commercial links between the principal towns of Khorasan. This book will provide the opportunity to better know the most recent elements of the principal constitutive sites of this geographical and political entity.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aClassical and Ancient Near Eastern StudiesxAncient Near Eastern Studies. 0aHistoryxHistorical PeriodsxMedieval History. 0aHistoryxTopics in HistoryxCultural History. 0aPhilosophyxPhilosophical Anthropology. 4aAfghanistan. 4aAusgrabung. 4aIran. 4aTurkmenistan. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / Iran.2bisacsh  aAfghanistan.  aIran.  aTurkmenistan.  aexcavations.1 aAdle, Chahryar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollin